// Using version 4.3.0 without compiler support
```

## Target State
```typescript
import react from "@vitejs/plugin-react";

export default defineConfig({
  plugins: [
    react({
      babel: {
        plugins: [
          ["babel-plugin-react-compiler", { 
            target: "19",
            // Enable source map support for debugging
            sources: (filename) => filename.includes("src/"),
          }]
        ]
      }
    })
  ]
});
```

## Why This Matters
- React Compiler automatically memoizes components and hooks
- Eliminates need for manual useMemo/useCallback in ~80% of cases
- Catches potential bugs at compile time (invalid deps, rules of hooks)
- Per Next.js 16 research: "Built-in support for the React Compiler is now stable following the React Compiler 1.0 release"
- Reduces cognitive load for developers

## Implementation Steps
1. Upgrade @vitejs/plugin-react to 5.0+
2. Install babel-plugin-react-compiler
3. Add compiler config to vite.config.ts
4. Add feature flag for quick disable if issues arise
5. Run full test suite
6. Verify build output shows compiler transformations

